  1. The connector vocabulary is richer than I thought — 6 variants, not 3:

  ┌────────┬───────────────────────┐
  │ Syntax │        Meaning        │
  ├────────┼───────────────────────┤
  │ >      │ left-to-right arrow   │
  ├────────┼───────────────────────┤
  │ <      │ right-to-left arrow   │
  ├────────┼───────────────────────┤
  │ <>     │ bidirectional arrow   │
  ├────────┼───────────────────────┤
  │ -      │ plain line (no arrow) │
  ├────────┼───────────────────────┤
  │ --     │ dotted line           │
  ├────────┼───────────────────────┤
  │ -->    │ dotted arrow          │
  └────────┴───────────────────────┘

  2. Multi-target + chained connections — one statement covers many edges:
  Server > Worker1, Worker2, Worker3     // fan-out
  Issue > Bug > Duplicate?               // chain

  3. Sequence diagrams have 5 block types (not 4):
  - loop, alt/else, opt, par/and, break

  …plus explicit lifeline activations:
  Client > Server: request
  activate Server
  Server > Client: response
  deactivate Server

  4. ER cardinality reuses < > <> but with different semantics than arch/sequence — this is the one syntactic subtlety in the whole grammar:

  ┌────────┬───────────────────────┬──────────────┐
  │ Symbol │ In arch/sequence/flow │    In ER     │
  ├────────┼───────────────────────┼──────────────┤
  │ >      │ left-to-right arrow   │ many-to-one  │
  ├────────┼───────────────────────┼──────────────┤
  │ <      │ right-to-left arrow   │ one-to-many  │
  ├────────┼───────────────────────┼──────────────┤
  │ -      │ plain line            │ one-to-one   │
  ├────────┼───────────────────────┼──────────────┤
  │ <>     │ bidirectional         │ many-to-many │
  └────────┴───────────────────────┴──────────────┘

  The parser has to be context-aware. Probably easiest by detecting an ER-style Entity { fields } block elsewhere in the doc and switching mode.

  5. ER allows in-line relationships inside the entity block — really nice:
  users [icon: user, color: blue] {
    id string pk
    teamId < teams.id     // declares both the FK column AND the relationship
  }

  6. Flowchart shapes — 11 of them:
  rectangle (default), cylinder, diamond, document, ellipse,
  hexagon, oval, parallelogram, star, trapezoid, triangle

