⏺ Yes — and there's a clear canonical answer. Let me lay out the tradeoff.

  What NotebookLM uses

  Google doesn't disclose it (their renderer is custom D3), but the open-source equivalent the community uses for the same UX is markmap — it's the de-facto "markdown → mindmap" library. NotebookLM-clones on GitHub (open-notebook, etc.) all
  reach for markmap. ~150k weekly npm downloads, MIT-licensed, mature.

  It comes in two pieces:

  - markmap-lib — parses a markdown bullet tree into a typed AST
  - markmap-view — D3-based interactive SVG renderer (zoom, pan, collapse, animated layout)

  Source format Claude has to emit is just nested markdown bullets:

  # OctoFocusAI
  ## AI co-author
  - /ai in notes
  - /ai on canvas
  - Voice in
  ## Cross-surface
  - Inline canvas embeds
  - @page mentions
  - Linked split view
  ## Findability
  - Cmd-K palette
  - Semantic search

  That's it. No DSL, no schema, no parser to write on our side.

  Three honest options for the mindmap artifact

  ┌─────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │                 │ tldraw + radial layout (what my DSL spec proposed) │                        markmap                         │                Mermaid mindmap                 │
  ├─────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Dependency cost │ None new; reuses our canvas                        │ markmap-lib + markmap-view (~80kb gz, well-maintained) │ None new (we already use Mermaid in BlockNote) │
  ├─────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Visual quality  │ We have to design it                               │ Beautiful by default — looks like NotebookLM           │ Static, no zoom/pan, limited styling           │
  ├─────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Editability     │ Full visual edit on the canvas                     │ Read-only by default                                   │ Read-only                                      │
  ├─────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Source format   │ Custom DSL (we'd write the parser)                 │ Plain markdown bullets (Claude trivially emits)        │ Mermaid mindmap syntax (Claude knows it)       │
  ├─────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Time to ship    │ ~3 days (parser + radial layout + tldraw bindings) │ ~2 hours (npm install + a wrapper component)           │ ~1 hour (already wired)                        │
  ├─────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Interactivity   │ Drag/edit shapes                                   │ Collapse nodes, zoom, pan                              │ None                                           │
  └─────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  Recommendation: do both, for different surfaces

  The two use cases want different renderers:

  - Canvas "mindmap" diagram type (in the DSL spec I just wrote, §7) → keep tldraw. Users want to grab nodes and edit. Editable beats pretty here.
  - Mindmap artifact derived from a doc (NotebookLM-style — what you actually asked about) → use markmap. It's read-only, gorgeous, takes Claude-emitted markdown directly, and lands in ~2 hours instead of 3 days.

  This is the same split-personality approach as our notes side: BlockNote for editable, custom renderer for the read-only public view.

  Updated artifact build order

  If we use markmap for the mindmap artifact, the build sequence flips:

  1. ~~Mindmap (canvas + DSL) — 3 days~~ → Mindmap (markmap artifact) — half a day. Now the simplest of the four.
  2. Flashcards — pure data + flip-card UI (~1 day)
  3. Quiz — extends flashcards with scoring (~1 day)
  4. Infographic — still the hardest; needs custom tldraw shape vocabulary (~3-5 days)

  So mindmap moves to first because it's cheapest, and the DSL v2 work decouples — that's a longer-term project for the canvas pillar, not blocking the artifact ship.

